If you love a senior dog, this post is for you. A short while ago we reconnected with @abrionesphoto (who once photographed Gert and the girls) about a project she’s doing. She’s photographing senior dogs and the people who love them, and her hope is to publish a book of photos and letters from the people to the pups. Well we got our photos (more spam coming) and I wrote my letter…woof. Thinking about your dog’s eyebrows getting gray, the time you’ve spent vs the time you have left, the things you’ll miss, the things maybe you even won’t, the emptiness that waits, the gratitude for every day together. It’s overwhelming. But I love this project so much and I’m so glad we got to be a part of it. •
If this sounds like a project that’s right for you and your pup, reach out to @abrionesphoto and tell her Pigpen sent ya ❤️.

This is her ideal place to be. •

2022, what a year. It felt like a whole lot of years packed into one didn’t it? We started with an 8 month old and we’re ending with a 20 month old and if you know toddlers that’s a crazy difference. He learned to walk, start talking, and most importantly started demanding to give the dogs treats. We had to let Scully go after a very long, hard 3 months of decline. We celebrated A’s first birthday. We took our first plane trips with a kid. We moved from our home of the last 6 years in LIC out to a house in Long Island. We continued to see Loo’s oncologist in the city every few months as protocol to make sure if anything ever rescues with her cancer we catch it early. We watched Penny get a little whiter but not any less crazy. I put ears on Gert. We hit 9 years together (and our 3rd wedding anniversary). Loosey’s 5 year, Penny’s 7 year adoptiversary. We navigated changing dynamics, relationships, locations, and more. 2022 was overall very kind to us. We hope 2023 will be the same ❤️ love to all who still show up for our journey even though we (I) have been so bad with posting lately. More of the Pig Fam adventures next year! 
Love,
Sam, Eric, A, Pen, and Loo (and Scully’s ghost)

8 years ago we met an emaciated, sick, starved little brown dog. 8 years later she is the queen of our hearts and our home. She has her moments but she is the sweetest, most loving, most wonderful Pig in the world. We can’t imagine our lives without her. She’s made us who we are today. 8 adoptiversaries down, many, we hope, to go. Merry Pigmas today and always. The sun in our stars, moon of our hearts, breaker of crates, ruler of the apartment, queen of dogs and the first men. Long may she reign. 👑

I looked up last night and just started hysterically laughing, couldn’t even explain, because how could you even explain this. That frickin turkey foot just popping out her side indicating she is fully roasted. 💀

Today marks the end of an era. We officially sold our apartment in LIC. We moved there when we’d had Penny for about a year and a half, in 2016, and left almost exactly 6 years later. We can’t thank that apartment enough for seeing us through an engagement (literally), a pandemic, working from home, adopting 2 dogs, letting 2 dogs go, fostering maybe 80 dogs, a pregnancy, postpartum, and everything that goes with all of that. Pig’s House was the stuff of legends. We may never again have a moment in time like the one we had there, though it was actually almost a decade in the end. We grew up in that apartment. I threw up a lot in that apartment, slept in dog beds, and also learned to be a mom. What growth that apartment saw in us, in me. Loosey was a puppy there, and left as a 6 year old dog. Gert and Scully lived and died peacefully there. Our son learned to eat, crawl, walk, become obsessed with dogs. Our little piece of NYC. We will never forget that apartment and we wish the new owners so much love and enjoyment…I was extremely happy to learn another dog will be moving in to enjoy that back patio space 🥹. So cheers to the first Pig Mama’s House, and to all who came through it. #PigofQueens forever.

And that’s a wrap on A’s first foster!! (Unless you count Scully, which I don’t because he wasn’t a foster so much as a cantankerous uncle). We picked up little Fiora last night at JFK from @dogsandcatsantigua and after a bath, a good night’s sleep, some good playtime and 2 breakfasts we brought her to @animalleague where we hope she’ll be scooped up fast by a family who loves her. A did awesome. He was really excited at first, then said “fifi too crazy. Dada, fifi go home” 😂 then warmed up and liked her by the end of the 5 hours he spent with her haha. The girls did absolutely amazing. Excited and then over it. Even Lenny mostly kept her cool. All in all it was a great experience for our fam and we’re excited to do it again…just not for a few weeks maybe 😅. We hope you have a happy life Fiora/Fifi/Stinky!! #103

In all seriousness, it took us 8 years to get to this point wjth Penny. She had never seen a leash before most likely and we tried EVERYTHING to get her to be pleasant on a leash. When your dog isn’t fun to walk, it’s not fun to walk with them. For anyone dealing with that, I feel you. But now, with consistency, time, age, a quiet neighborhood and humidity, I had the BEST stroll with them today. And I kept thinking to myself…this is so wonderful. They both walked so calmly with loose leashes by my sides and I could feel myself beaming with pride. I was so proud to walk with my girls. So if you’re struggling, keep going. We believe in you.
